"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872660","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-04-05","<p>The Government remains vigilant about the inequalities experienced by Gypsy, Roma and Traveller communities, and the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government has brought forward a new and ambitious integration strategy. The Integrated Communities Strategy Green Paper, published in March, invites views on the Government’s vision for building strong integrated communities where people – whatever their background – live, work, learn and socialise together, based on shared rights, responsibilities and opportunities. We encourage all groups, including Gypsy, Roma and Traveller communities, to engage with the Green Paper.</p><p> </p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-04-05T15:58:46.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872660/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872660/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872660/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-27","Travellers: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to create a Roma integration strategy for after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","134474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872661","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-29","<p>The table below gives the average bus occupancy on local bus services in England from 20014/15 to 2016/17.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Average bus occupancy<sup>1</sup> on local bus services: England, 2014/15 to 2016/17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average bus occupancy</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>12.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>11.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>11.9</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>1 Calculated as passenger miles divided by vehicle miles.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-03-29T13:11:58.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872661/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872661/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872661/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-27","Buses: Passengers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of passengers per public bus journey in England in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","John Redwood","134475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872662","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-09","<p>Our manifesto made it clear that we would take early steps to control the export of live farm animals for slaughter, once we leave the European Union, and we are currently considering options.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-04-09T13:49:28.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872662/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872662/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-27","Livestock: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to improve standards of animal welfare in transit after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","John Redwood","134476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872663","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-05","<p>The government has announced that it will introduce a Fisheries Bill during this session of parliament and will shortly publish a White Paper in advance of the Bill. The White Paper will set out the government's vision for an independent fisheries policy for the UK's Exclusive Economic Zone.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-04-05T16:25:20.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872663/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872663/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-27","Fisheries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when the Government plans to announce its policy on fishing for after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","John Redwood","134477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872664","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-04-05","<p>We promote Access to Work through engagement with partners and stakeholders such as Remploy, as well as through other government departments and public sector bodies. Access to Work is also promoted to a range of business leaders through the Disability Confident scheme. As part of the ongoing Access to Work scheme, partnership managers will be engaging with local contacts to promote the support available.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-04-05T14:51:48.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872664/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872664/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-27","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps her Department is taking to raise awareness of the availability of access to work grants.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","134478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872665","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-04-05","<p>The information on how many people are in receipt of Access to Work grants by region is not readily available and has not previously been published as official statistics. We will consider whether it is feasible to produce the statistics requested and, if so, will issue them in an official statistics release in accordance with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics.</p><p>Official experimental statistics are available on the number of people who had Access to Work provision approved from the financial year between 2007/08 and 2016/17, these statistics show the number of people who had Access to Work provision approved by the type of provision, age, gender and primary medical condition. Access to Work provision was approved for 25,020 individuals in 2016/17 – an 8% increase on 2015/16, at a cost of £104m</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/access-to-work-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/access-to-work-statistics</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-04-05T14:56:44.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872665/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872665/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-27","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people are in receipt of access to work grants by region.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","134479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872666","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-04-05","<p>The Written Ministerial Statement of 20 March on Access to Work announced that the Access to Work award limit, currently £42,100 per year, will rise from 1<sup>st</sup> April 2018 to £57,200 per annum. This will make available an increased level of potential support to those using Access to Work. We have committed to the ongoing monitoring of the impact of the cap and intend to publish an update to the Equality Analysis published in May 2015 as a formal addendum.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/future-of-access-to-work" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/future-of-access-to-work</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-04-05T14:54:40.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872666/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872666/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-27","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the effect of the cap on access to work grants on progress in reducing the disability employment gap.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","134480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872667","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-04-16","<p>There have been no such meetings<strong>.</strong></p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-04-16T10:38:41.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872667/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872667/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-27","Department for Work and Pensions: Cambridge Analytica and SCL Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether she or her predecessors met with representatives of the SCL group or Cambridge Analytica; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","134481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872668","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-04","<p>NHS England has advised that it is expected that the recommendations from the relative prioritisation process will be received by the Specialised Services Commissioning Committee (SSCC) meeting on 19 June 2018. The aim will be to communicate the results as soon as possible following the SSCC meeting.</p><p>A process of relative prioritisation for determining discretionary investment in new specialised services was first introduced in 2016/17. Investment decisions are informed following advice from NHS England’s independently chaired Clinical Priorities Advisory Group and against a budget that is fixed annually. In 2016/17 and again in 2017/18, £25 million was set aside for this purpose. This was considered an appropriate level of investment in the context of NHS England’s Specialised Commissioning function having to achieve overall efficiency savings of approximately 2.7% and approximately 2.5% in 2016/17 and 2017/18 respectively in order to meet the financial pressures resulting from demographic growth and the legal requirement to fund all positive National Institute for Health and Care Excellence technology appraisals. Once funding is distributed following this relative prioritisation process, spend is not separately monitored.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","134484 ; 134486","2018-04-04T13:20:07.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872668/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872668/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872668/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-27","Clinical Priorities Advisory Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February to Question 128018, on Clinical Priorities Advisory Group, on what date NHS England plans to announce (a) announce the results of the prioritisation process and (b) make funding available for approved medicines policies.","false","Biography information for Mark Tami","Alyn and Deeside","Mark Tami","134482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872669","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-04-16","<p>The Department’s e-procurement system does not hold any created/active/archived/terminated contracts with SCL Group or Cambridge Analytica.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-04-16T10:36:20.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872669/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/872669/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-27","Department for Work and Pensions: Cambridge Analytica and SCL Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether her Department or any of it agencies or associated public bodies has had contracts with SCL group or Cambridge Analytica; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","134483"
